{"title_page": "Ralph Glyn, 1st Baron Glyn", "text_new": "[[Major]] '''Ralph George Campbell Glyn, 1st Baron Glyn''', [[Military Cross|MC]], [[Deputy Lieutenant|DL]] (3 March 1884 \u2013 1 May 1960), known as '''Sir Ralph Glyn, Bt''', from 1934 to 1953, was a soldier and [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] politician in the [[United Kingdom]]. He was a [[Member of Parliament]] (MP) from 1918 to 1922, and from 1924 to 1953.\n\n==Early life==\nGlyn was born on 3 March 1884 to [[Edward Glyn]], [[Bishop of Peterborough]] and Lady Emma Mary, daughter of [[George Campbell, 8th Duke of Argyll]]. His father was the younger son of [[George Glyn, 1st Baron Wolverton]]. He was educated at [[Wixenford School|Wixenford]], [[Harrow School|Harrow]], and the [[Royal Military College, Sandhurst]].<ref>'Glyn, 1st Baron', in ''Who Was Who 1951\u20131960'' (A. & C. Black, 1984 reprint, {{ISBN|0-7136-2598-8}})</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\n===Military service===\nGlyn fought in the [[First World War]], during which he was [[mentioned in despatches]] and was awarded the [[Military Cross]].<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=30450 |date=1 January 1918 |page=36 |supp=y}}</ref>\n\n===Political career===\nAt the [[1918 United Kingdom general election|1918 general election]], Glyn was elected as Unionist MP for the Scottish constituency of [[Clackmannan and Eastern Stirlingshire (UK Parliament constituency)|Clackmannan and Eastern Stirlingshire]]. However he lost the seat at the [[1922 United Kingdom general election|1922 general election]], coming third with 28% of the votes. The following year, at the [[1923 United Kingdom general election|1923 general election]], Glyn stood in the  Conservative-held seat of [[Abingdon (UK Parliament constituency)|Abingdon]], where the MP [[Arthur Thomas Loyd|Arthur Loyd]] was not standing again. Lloyd's majority in 1922 had been only 640 votes, and Glyn lost by 254 votes (1.2% of the total) to the [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal]] candidate [[Edward Albert Lessing|Edward Lessing]].\n\nHowever, at the [[1924 United Kingdom general election|1924 general election]], Glyn substantially increased his vote,  and won the seat with a majority of over 4,000 votes.  He represented the constituency for nearly thirty years, and was returned unopposed at the [[1931 United Kingdom general election|1931 election]] and at the [[1935 United Kingdom general election|1935 election]]. He was made a baronet 21 January 1934, of Farnborough Downs, in the County of [[Berkshire]],<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=34018 |date=26 January 1934 |page=604}}</ref> and in 1953 he was elevated to the peerage as '''Baron Glyn''', of Farnborough in the County of Berkshire.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=39904 |date=3 July 1953 |page=3677 }}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nLord Glyn married Sibell Vanden Bempde-Johnstone, daughter of Francis Vanden-Bempde-Johnstone, 2nd Baron Derwent and widow of Brigadier-General [[Walter Long (general)|Walter Long]], in 1921. She was the mother of [[Walter Long, 2nd Viscount Long]]. There were no children from the marriage. Lady Glyn died in 1958. Lord Glyn survived her by two years and died in [[Oxfordshire]] in 1960, aged 75, when the baronetcy and barony became extinct.\n\nGlyn was on the governing body of [[Abingdon School]] from 1924-1952 and again from 1955\u20131960 in addition to be the Vice-chairman of the Governors from 1958 until his death in 1960.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.abingdon.org.uk/uploads/school/files/abingdonian/1942_Summer_V008_N004.pdf#page=11|title=1942 Summer Abingdonian|publisher=Abingdon School}}</ref> and the [[Mayor]] of Abingdon.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://friendsofabingdon.org.uk/about-us/history/2/|title=History of the FoA|publisher=Friends of Abingdon Civic Society}}</ref>\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== References ==\n* {{cite book |last=Craig |first=F. W. S. |authorlink= F. W. S. Craig  |title=British parliamentary election results 1918-1949 |origyear=1969 |edition= 3rd |year=1983 |publisher= Parliamentary Research Services |location=Chichester |isbn= 0-900178-06-X}}\n*{{Rayment|date=February 2012}}\n*{{Rayment-hc|date=March 2012}}\n*{{cite web |last=Lundy |first=Darryl |url=http://www.thepeerage.com/info.htm |title=FAQ |publisher= The Peerage}}{{Unreliable source?|failed=y |date=February 2013}}<!--Lundy is not a reliable source so cite Lundy's reliable source See [[WP:SAYWHEREYOUREADIT]]-->\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Hansard-contribs | colonel-ralph-glyn | Ralph Glyn }}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-new | constituency }}\n{{s-ttl\n  | title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for {{nowrap|[[Clackmannan and Eastern Stirlingshire (UK Parliament constituency)|Clackmannan & Eastern Stirlingshire]]}}\n  | years  = [[1918 United Kingdom general election|1918]]\u2013[[1922 United Kingdom general election|1922]]\n}}\n{{s-aft | after  = [[MacNeill Weir]] }}\n{{succession box\n  | title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Abingdon (UK Parliament constituency)|Abingdon]]\n  | years  = [[1924 United Kingdom general election|1924]]\u2013[[1953 Abingdon by-election|1953]]\n  | before = [[Edward Lessing]]\n  | after  = [[Airey Neave]]\n}}\n{{s-reg|uk}}\n{{s-new | creation}}\n{{s-ttl\n  | title  = [[Baron Glyn]]\n  | years  = 1953\u20131960\n}}\n{{s-non | reason = Extinct }}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2012}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Glyn, Ralph}}\n[[Category:1884 births]]\n[[Category:1960 deaths]]\n[[Category:Barons in the Peerage of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:People educated at Harrow School]]\n[[Category:People educated at Wixenford School]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for Stirling constituencies]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1918\u20131922]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1924\u20131929]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1929\u20131931]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1931\u20131935]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1935\u20131945]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1945\u20131950]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1950\u20131951]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1951\u20131955]]\n[[Category:Glyn family|Ralph]]\n[[Category:Unionist Party (Scotland) MPs]]\n[[Category:Governors of Abingdon School]]\n", "text_old": "[[Major]] '''Ralph George Campbell Glyn, 1st Baron Glyn''', [[Military Cross|MC]], [[Deputy Lieutenant|DL]] (3 March 1884 \u2013 1 May 1960), known as '''Sir Ralph Glyn, Bt''', from 1934 to 1953, was a soldier and [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] politician in the [[United Kingdom]]. He was a [[Member of Parliament]] (MP) from 1918 to 1922, and from 1924 to 1953.\n\n==Early life==\nGlyn was born on 3 March 1884 to [[Edward Glyn]], [[Bishop of Peterborough]] and Lady Emma Mary, daughter of [[George Campbell, 8th Duke of Argyll]]. His father was the younger son of [[George Glyn, 1st Baron Wolverton]]. He was educated at [[Wixenford School|Wixenford]], [[Harrow School|Harrow]], and the [[Royal Military College, Sandhurst]].<ref>'Glyn, 1st Baron', in ''Who Was Who 1951\u20131960'' (A. & C. Black, 1984 reprint, {{ISBN|0-7136-2598-8}})</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\n===Military service===\nGlyn fought in the [[First World War]], during which he was [[mentioned in despatches]] and was awarded the [[Military Cross]].<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=30450 |date=1 January 1918 |page=36 |supp=y}}</ref>\n\n===Political career===\nAt the [[1918 United Kingdom general election|1918 general election]], Glyn was elected as Unionist MP for the Scottish constituency of [[Clackmannan and Eastern Stirlingshire (UK Parliament constituency)|Clackmannan and Eastern Stirlingshire]]. However he lost the seat at the [[1922 United Kingdom general election|1922 general election]], coming third with 28% of the votes. The following year, at the [[1923 United Kingdom general election|1923 general election]], Glyn stood in the  Conservative-held seat of [[Abingdon (UK Parliament constituency)|Abingdon]], where the MP [[Arthur Thomas Loyd|Arthur Loyd]] was not standing again. Lloyd's majority in 1922 had been only 640 votes, and Glyn lost by 254 votes (1.2% of the total) to the [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal]] candidate [[Edward Albert Lessing|Edward Lessing]].\n\nHowever, at the [[1924 United Kingdom general election|1924 general election]], Glyn substantially increased his vote,  and won the seat with a majority of over 4,000 votes.  He represented the constituency for nearly thirty years, and was returned unopposed at the [[1931 United Kingdom general election|1931 election]] and at the [[1935 United Kingdom general election|1935 election]]. He was made a baronet 21 January 1934, of Farnborough Downs, in the County of [[Berkshire]],<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=34018 |date=26 January 1934 |page=604}}</ref> and in 1953 he was elevated to the peerage as '''Baron Glyn''', of Farnborough in the County of Berkshire.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=39904 |date=3 July 1953 |page=3677 }}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nLord Glyn married Sibell Vanden Bempde-Johnstone, daughter of Francis Vanden-Bempde-Johnstone, 2nd Baron Derwent and widow of Brigadier-General [[Walter Long (general)|Walter Long]], in 1921. She was the mother of [[Walter Long, 2nd Viscount Long]]. There were no children from the marriage. Lady Glyn died in 1958. Lord Glyn survived her by two years and died in [[Oxfordshire]] in 1960, aged 75, when the baronetcy and barony became extinct.\n\nGlyn was on the governing body of [[Abingdon School]] from 1924-1952 and again from 1955-1960 in addition to be the Vice-chairman of the Governors from 1958 until his death in 1960.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.abingdon.org.uk/uploads/school/files/abingdonian/1942_Summer_V008_N004.pdf#page=11|title=1942 Summer Abingdonian|publisher=Abingdon School}}</ref> and the [[Mayor]] of Abingdon.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://friendsofabingdon.org.uk/about-us/history/2/|title=History of the FoA|publisher=Friends of Abingdon Civic Society}}</ref>\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== References ==\n* {{cite book |last=Craig |first=F. W. S. |authorlink= F. W. S. Craig  |title=British parliamentary election results 1918-1949 |origyear=1969 |edition= 3rd |year=1983 |publisher= Parliamentary Research Services |location=Chichester |isbn= 0-900178-06-X}}\n*{{Rayment|date=February 2012}}\n*{{Rayment-hc|date=March 2012}}\n*{{cite web |last=Lundy |first=Darryl |url=http://www.thepeerage.com/info.htm |title=FAQ |publisher= The Peerage}}{{Unreliable source?|failed=y |date=February 2013}}<!--Lundy is not a reliable source so cite Lundy's reliable source See [[WP:SAYWHEREYOUREADIT]]-->\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Hansard-contribs | colonel-ralph-glyn | Ralph Glyn }}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-new | constituency }}\n{{s-ttl\n  | title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for {{nowrap|[[Clackmannan and Eastern Stirlingshire (UK Parliament constituency)|Clackmannan & Eastern Stirlingshire]]}}\n  | years  = [[1918 United Kingdom general election|1918]]\u2013[[1922 United Kingdom general election|1922]]\n}}\n{{s-aft | after  = [[MacNeill Weir]] }}\n{{succession box\n  | title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Abingdon (UK Parliament constituency)|Abingdon]]\n  | years  = [[1924 United Kingdom general election|1924]]\u2013[[1953 Abingdon by-election|1953]]\n  | before = [[Edward Lessing]]\n  | after  = [[Airey Neave]]\n}}\n{{s-reg|uk}}\n{{s-new | creation}}\n{{s-ttl\n  | title  = [[Baron Glyn]]\n  | years  = 1953\u20131960\n}}\n{{s-non | reason = Extinct }}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2012}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Glyn, Ralph}}\n[[Category:1884 births]]\n[[Category:1960 deaths]]\n[[Category:Barons in the Peerage of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:People educated at Harrow School]]\n[[Category:People educated at Wixenford School]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for Stirling constituencies]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1918\u20131922]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1924\u20131929]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1929\u20131931]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1931\u20131935]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1935\u20131945]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1945\u20131950]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1950\u20131951]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1951\u20131955]]\n[[Category:Glyn family|Ralph]]\n[[Category:Unionist Party (Scotland) MPs]]\n[[Category:Governors of Abingdon School]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePersonal life:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 1955-1960 \u2192 1955\u20131960", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ralph_Glyn,_1st_Baron_Glyn"}
{"title_page": "George Gavan Duffy", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=October 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name          = George Gavan Duffy\n| image         = George Gavan Duffy.jpg\n| caption       = Portrait of George Gavan Duffy by Sir [[John Lavery]]\n| office        = President of the [[High Court (Ireland)|High Court]]\n| term_start    = 4 May 1946\n| term_end      = 20 June 1951\n| nominator     = [[Government of the 12th D\u00e1il|Government of Ireland]]\n| appointer     = [[Se\u00e1n T. O'Kelly]]\n| predecessor   = [[Conor Maguire]]\n| successor     = [[Cahir Davitt]]\n| office1       = Judge of the [[High Court (Ireland)|High Court]]\n| term_start1   = 2 July 1936\n| term_end1     = 20 June 1951\n| nominator1    = [[Government of the 8th D\u00e1il|Government of Ireland]]\n| appointer1    = [[Domhnall Ua Buachalla]]\n| office2       = [[Minister for Foreign Affairs and Trade|Minister for Foreign Affairs]] \n| president2    = [[Michael Collins (Irish leader)|Michael Collins]]\n| term_start2   = 10 January 1922\n| term_end2     = 25 July 1922\n| predecessor2  = [[Arthur Griffith]]\n| successor2    = Arthur Griffith\n| office3       = [[Teachta D\u00e1la]]\n| term_start3   = [[1921 Irish elections|May 1921]]\n| term_end3     = [[1923 Irish general election|August 1923]] \n| constituency3 = [[Dublin County (D\u00e1il constituency)|Dublin County]]\n| office4       = [[Member of Parliament]]<br>for [[South County Dublin (UK Parliament constituency)|South County Dublin]]\n| term_start4   = 14 December 1918\n| term_end4     = 24 May 1921\n| predecessor4  = [[Michael Louis Hearn]]\n| successor4    = Office abolished\n| birth_name    = George Gavan Duffy\n| birth_date    = {{birth date|1882|10|21|df=y}}\n| birth_place   = [[Rock Ferry]], United Kingdom\n| death_date    = {{death date and age|1951|6|10|1882|10|21|df=y}}\n| death_place   = [[Terenure]], [[Dublin]], Ireland\n| nationality   = [[Irish people|Irish]]\n| party         = [[Cumann na nGaedheal]]\n| spouse        = Margaret Sullivan<br>{{small|(m. 1908; d. 1951)}} \n| children      = 2\n| relations     = {{Ubl|[[Charles Gavan Duffy]] (Father)|[[Frank Gavan Duffy]] (Half-Brother)|[[Louise Gavan Duffy]] (Sister)}}\n| education     = [[Stonyhurst College]]\n| alma_mater    = [[University of London]]\n|}}\n'''George Gavan Duffy''' ({{lang-ga|Seoirse Gabh\u00e1n \u00d3 Dubhthaigh}}; 21 October 1882 \u2013 10 June 1951) was an Irish politician, barrister and judge who served as President of the [[High Court (Ireland)|High Court]] from 1946 to 1951, a Judge of the [[High Court (Ireland)|High Court]] from 1936 to 1951 and [[Minister for Foreign Affairs and Trade|Minister for Foreign Affairs]] from January 1922 to July 1922. He served as a [[Teachta D\u00e1la]]\n(TD) for the [[Dublin County (D\u00e1il constituency)|Dublin County]] constituency from 1921 to 1923. He served as a [[Member of Parliament]] (MP) for the [[South County Dublin (UK Parliament constituency)|South County Dublin]] constituency from 1918 to 1921.<ref name=oireachtas_db>{{cite web|url=https://www.oireachtas.ie/en/members/member/George-Gavan-Duffy.D.1919-01-21/|title=George Gavan Duffy|work=Oireachtas Members Database|access-date=12 February 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Family==\n{{unreferenced section|date=March 2016}}\nGeorge Gavan Duffy was born at Rose Cottage, [[Rock Ferry]], [[Cheshire]], England, in 1882, the son of [[Charles Gavan Duffy|Sir Charles Gavan Duffy]] and his third wife, Louise (n\u00e9e Hall). His half-brother [[Frank Gavan Duffy|Sir Frank Gavan Duffy]] (1852\u20131936) was the fourth Chief Justice of the [[High Court of Australia]], sitting on the bench of the High Court from 1913\u201335.\n\nHis sister [[Louise Gavan Duffy]] came to Ireland in 1907, he taught in [[Patrick Pearse]]'s St Ita's school for girls ''Scoil \u00cdde'', was, with [[Mary Colum]] first Secretary of ''Cumann na mBan'', was out in the [[Easter Rising]] of 1916, in the GPO and Jacob's garrisons. She founded and ran ''Scoil Bhr\u00edde'', a bilingual school in [[Dublin]], which is still in operation. Louise came originally to Dublin, as her mother died in 1889.  George was raised by three half-sisters travelling from [[Austria]] and [[Germany]], at Guilloy, [[Nice]], [[France]]. He spoke fluent Italian and French received education from ''Petit Seminaire''. From there he was sent to [[Stonyhurst College]].\n\nHe qualified with a solicitor's firm in London in 1907. He married Margaret Sullivan, on 13 December 1908. They had two children, a son (Colum) and a daughter (M\u00e1ire). Colum Duffy was a legal scholar and law librarian at the [[Law Society of Ireland]].{{citation needed|date=March 2016}}\n\n==Early career==\nGavan Duffy qualified as a solicitor and practised in London. He defended [[Roger Casement|Sir Roger Casement]] at his trial for [[high treason]] after the Easter Rising. Although the case was unsuccessful and Casement executed, the trial had an enormous effect on Gavan Duffy and in 1917, when he was called to the [[Irish Bar]], he came to live in [[King's Inns]], Dublin, where he became immersed in Irish political life.\n\n==Political life==\n\n===Recognition efforts===\n{{more citations needed section|date=March 2016}}\nDuring the [[1918 Irish general election|1918 Westminster election]], he was elected as a [[Sinn F\u00e9in]] [[Member of Parliament|MP]] for [[South Dublin (UK Parliament constituency)|South County Dublin]].<ref name=elecs_irl>{{cite web|url=http://electionsireland.org/candidate.cfm?ID=1000|title=George Gavan Duffy|work=ElectionsIreland.org|accessdate=12 February 2012}}</ref>\n\nHe was sent to Paris to join [[Se\u00e1n T. O'Kelly]], as an envoy of the newly declared [[Irish Republic]]. Gavan Duffy published articles and pamphlets urging recognition of Ireland as a sovereign nation at the [[Paris Peace Conference, 1919|Paris Peace Conference]], which caused increasing embarrassment to the French establishment, who believed his publications were damaging Anglo-French relations.\n\nGavan Duffy and O'Kelly sought France's help against Britain when the treaties ending the [[First World War]] had not yet been signed; Britain had been France's main ally for most of the war, in which France had suffered enormous losses. In January 1919, the Sinn F\u00e9in-affiliated [[Irish Republican Army]] had also started the [[Anglo-Irish War|Irish War of Independence]] against Britain, and the new [[D\u00e1il]] had [[Irish Declaration of Independence|declared independence]] from the United Kingdom.\n\nFurther, the British position was that it was preparing a revised system of Irish Home Rule which would be effected after the Peace Conference, and that it had tried to solve the Irish Question at the [[Irish Convention]] in 1917, which Sinn F\u00e9in had boycotted. Sinn F\u00e9in had joined in the [[Conscription Crisis of 1918|campaign against conscription]] in 1918.\n\nIn consequence all the [[Allies of World War I]] saw the Sinn F\u00e9in movement as more or less hostile. A final letter of June 1919 demanding recognition and addressed to the French Prime Minister [[Georges Clemenceau]], the chairman of the Peace Conference, was not replied to.<ref>See [[National Archives of Ireland|NAI]] file DFA ES Paris 1919; Official Memorandum in support of Ireland's demand for recognition as a sovereign independent state. Presented to Georges Clemenceau and the members of the Paris Peace Conference by Sean T. O'Ceallaigh and George Gavan Duffy.</ref>\n\nFinally, after publishing a letter he had sent to Clemenceau in protest against the former mistreatment of [[Terence MacSwiney]] in prison in 1917, Gavan Duffy was banished from Paris. He was declared ''persona non grata'' in December 1920. He then went to Rome and from there travelled through Europe on behalf of the Ministry of the Irish Republic, without securing its recognition.\n\n===Anglo-Irish Treaty===\n[[File:The peacemakers- George Gavan Duffy, Erskine Childers, Robert Barton and Arthur Griffith in a group (28455606301).jpg|thumb|Duffy together with other members of the negotiation team (including Childers, Griffith, and Barton) in December 1921]]\nWhen [[\u00c9amon de Valera]] chose his plenipotentiaries to negotiate the [[Anglo-Irish Treaty]] in 1921; Gavan Duffy was chosen due mainly to his legal expertise. He protested against signing the Treaty but did so reluctantly, becoming the last person to sign. During the debates which followed in [[D\u00e1il \u00c9ireann]], Gavan Duffy stated that he would recommend the Treaty reluctantly but sincerely as he saw no alternative for the desired aim of independence.\n\n<blockquote>I do not love this treaty now any more than I loved it when I signed it, that I do not think that...is an adequate motive for rejection to point out that some of us signed the Treaty under duress, not to say that this treaty will not lead to permanent peace.  It is necessary before you reject the Treaty to go further than that and to produce to the people of Ireland a rational alternative.  My heart is with those who are against the Treaty, but my reason is against them, because I can see no rational alternative.<ref>D\u00e1il Debates, 21 December 1921</ref></blockquote>\n\nGavan Duffy placed the onus on the people who were responsible for drafting the Constitution of the Irish Free State to frame it in accordance with the terms of the Treaty. He disagreed, however, with Griffith's decision to show the draft constitution to [[British Prime Minister]] [[David Lloyd George|Lloyd George]] who immediately ordered that references to the [[King of the United Kingdom|King]] had to be inserted as well as an Oath of Allegiance. Lloyd George threatened to start a war if the Irish refused to sign; but Gavan Duffy did not believe it.\n\nOn 21 December 1921, he gave his main reason for supporting the treaty in the Dail, the impact of a potentially renewed war on the people, concluding:\n<blockquote>You may gamble on the prospects of a renewal of that horrible war, which I for one have only seen from afar, but which I know those who have so nobly withstood do not wish to see begun again without a clear prospect of getting further than they are to-day. We are told that this is a surrender of principle. If that be so, we must be asked to believe that every one of those who have gone before us in previous fights, and who in the end have had to lay down their arms or surrender to avert a greater evil to the people, have likewise been guilty of a breach of principle. I do not think an argument of that kind will get you much further. No! The solid principle, the solid basis upon which every honest man ought to make up his mind on this issue, may be summed up in the principle that we all claimed when it was first enunciated by the President, the principle of government by the [[consent of the governed]]. I say that no serious person here, whatever his feelings, knowing as he must what the people of this country think of the matter, will be doing his duty if, under these circumstances, he refuses to ratify the Treaty. Ratify it with the most dignified protest you can, ratify because you cannot do otherwise, but ratify it in the interests of the people you must.</blockquote>\n\n===Resignations===\nThis prompted him to resign but he was compelled to remain in office, serving as [[Minister for Foreign Affairs and Trade|Minister for Foreign Affairs]] from January 1922 to July 1922. On the outbreak of the [[Irish Civil War]] he resigned when the Provisional Government refused to effect a court order for [[habeas corpus]] in favour of [[George Plunkett (Irish Republican)|George Plunkett]] (a son of [[George Noble Plunkett|Count Plunkett]]), who was detained without charge with other republicans.\n\nHis tenure in office was cut short by his decision to resign again when the [[Executive Council of the Irish Free State]] abolished the Republican Courts and executed his good friend [[Erskine Childers (author)|Erskine Childers]].\n\nHe stood in the [[1923 Irish general election|1923 general election]] as an independent candidate but failed to be re-elected.\n\n==Barrister and judge==\n{{more citations needed|section|date=December 2017}}\nGavan Duffy returned to the [[Irish Bar]] and built up a large practice and was engaged in some notable constitutional cases such as the Land Annuities controversy in which he claimed that the [[Irish Free State]] could not be bound either in honour or in law to hand over annuities to Britain. He was appointed [[Senior Counsel]] in 1930 and Judge of the [[High Court (Ireland)|High Court]] in 1936. He acted as an unofficial legal advisor to [[\u00c9amon de Valera]] during the drafting of the 1937 [[Constitution of Ireland]] and was consulted on many issues pertaining to it. He was also a member of the commission to set up the second house of the [[Oireachtas]], [[Seanad \u00c9ireann]], in 1937. As president of the High Court he issues the ruling in [[State (Burke) v. Lennon]] that was upheld by the Supreme Court of Ireland.\n\nIn 1946, at the height of his legal career, he was appointed President of the [[High Court (Ireland)|High Court]], a position he held for the rest of his life. His most controversial judgement was in the ''Tilson Case'' heard in 1950, one year before his death, in which he applied the ''[[ne temere]]'' decree to the letter as de Valera's 1937 Irish Constitution gave the [[Roman Catholic Church in Ireland]] a \"special position\".<ref>[[Irish Law Times]] Report vol.86 (1952) pp. 49\u201373</ref> The [[Supreme Court of Ireland]] concurred but Gavan Duffy was criticised in some quarters for  his ruling.<ref>Finola Kennedy, ''Family, economy and government in Ireland''; ESRI, Dublin (1989) pp. 70\u201371.</ref><ref>Donal Barrington, ''The family and education''; The Irish Monthly, Irish Jesuit Province, 1953.</ref> He was a longstanding member of the Catholic organisation [[An R\u00edoghacht]].<ref>Maurice Curtis, ''A Challenge to Democracy: Militant Catholicism in Modern Ireland'', The History Press Ireland, 2010, p. 55<!-- ISSN/ISBN needed --></ref>\n\nIn 1945, Gavan Duffy had extended the [[Benefit of clergy|privilege of clergy]] to evidence heard by Catholic priests hearing [[Sacrament of Penance (Catholic Church)|confessions]].<!-- to the effect that a priest was not obliged to repeat the evidence to any other party, including a court of law. NOTE: Hasn't this always been the law of the confessional?? --> Proposals to reverse the privilege were published in 2012.<!-- What came of them?? --><ref>''Irish Daily Mail'', 21 May 2012, pp 1, 8. The case was ''Cook v. Carroll'' (1945) Irish Reports 165; a pregnant girl and her boyfriend had both confessed their affair to a priest, and the girl's family wanted the father's admission of paternity to the priest to be repeated in a court case for [[child support]]. The man denied paternity and Gavan Duffy ruled that the priest was not obliged to repeat what he had heard in the man's confession.</ref>\n\n==Death==\nGeorge Gavan Duffy died at his home in Bushy Park Road, [[Terenure]], Dublin, on 10 June 1951.{{citation needed|date=December 2017}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*Golding, G.M. ''George Gavan Duffy 1882\u20131951: a legal biography'' (Dublin, 1982)\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110607092009/http://historical-debates.oireachtas.ie/D/DT/D.T.192112210002.html Gavan-Duffy's speech on 21 Dec 1921, pp.86\u201389]\n*[http://difp.ie/viewdoc.asp?DocID=13 Letter to Clemenceau demanding recognition,  June 1919]\n* {{cite TIWW |article=Duffy, George Gavan |page=70 }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before = [[Arthur Griffith]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title  = {{nowrap|[[Minister for Foreign Affairs and Trade|Minister for Foreign Affairs]]}}\n       |years  = Jan 1922 \u2013 Jul 1922}}\n{{s-aft|after  = [[Arthur Griffith]]}}\n{{end}}\n{{4th Ministry of D\u00e1il \u00c9ireann}}\n{{Ministers for Foreign Affairs of Ireland}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gavan Duffy, George}}\n[[Category:1882 births]]\n[[Category:1951 deaths]]\n[[Category:Early Sinn F\u00e9in TDs]]\n[[Category:Ministers for Foreign Affairs (Ireland)]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for County Dublin constituencies (1801\u20131922)]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1918\u20131922]]\n[[Category:Members of the 1st D\u00e1il]]\n[[Category:Members of the 2nd D\u00e1il]]\n[[Category:Members of the 3rd D\u00e1il]]\n[[Category:Irish lawyers]]\n[[Category:Irish barristers]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the High Court (Ireland)]]\n[[Category:Alumni of King's Inns]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=October 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name          = George Gavan Duffy\n| image         = George Gavan Duffy.jpg\n| caption       = Portrait of George Gavan Duffy by Sir [[John Lavery]]\n| office        = President of the [[High Court (Ireland)|High Court]]\n| term_start    = 4 May 1946\n| term_end      = 20 June 1951\n| nominator     = [[Government of the 12th D\u00e1il|Government of Ireland]]\n| appointer     = [[Se\u00e1n T. O'Kelly]]\n| predecessor   = [[Conor Maguire]]\n| successor     = [[Cahir Davitt]]\n| office1       = Judge of the [[High Court (Ireland)|High Court]]\n| term_start1   = 2 July 1936\n| term_end1     = 20 June 1951\n| nominator1    = [[Government of the 8th D\u00e1il|Government of Ireland]]\n| appointer1    = [[Domhnall Ua Buachalla]]\n| office2       = [[Minister for Foreign Affairs and Trade|Minister for Foreign Affairs]] \n| president2    = [[Michael Collins (Irish leader)|Michael Collins]]\n| term_start2   = 10 January 1922\n| term_end2     = 25 July 1922\n| predecessor2  = [[Arthur Griffith]]\n| successor2    = Arthur Griffith\n| office3       = [[Teachta D\u00e1la]]\n| term_start3   = [[1921 Irish elections|May 1921]]\n| term_end3     = [[1923 Irish general election|August 1923]] \n| constituency3 = [[Dublin County (D\u00e1il constituency)|Dublin County]]\n| office4       = [[Member of Parliament]]<br>for [[South County Dublin (UK Parliament constituency)|South County Dublin]]\n| term_start4   = 14 December 1918\n| term_end4     = 24 May 1921\n| predecessor4  = [[Michael Louis Hearn]]\n| successor4    = Office abolished\n| birth_name    = George Gavan Duffy\n| birth_date    = {{birth date|1882|10|21|df=y}}\n| birth_place   = [[Rock Ferry]], United Kingdom\n| death_date    = {{death date and age|1951|6|10|1882|10|21|df=y}}\n| death_place   = [[Terenure]], [[Dublin]], Ireland\n| nationality   = [[Irish people|Irish]]\n| party         = [[Cumann na nGaedheal]]\n| spouse        = Margaret Sullivan<br>{{small|(m. 1908; d. 1951)}} \n| children      = 2\n| relations     = {{Ubl|[[Charles Gavan Duffy]] (Father)|[[Frank Gavan Duffy]] (Half-Brother)|[[Louise Gavan Duffy]] (Sister)}}\n| education     = [[Stonyhurst College]]\n| alma_mater    = [[University of London]]\n|}}\n'''George Gavan Duffy''' ({{lang-ga|Seoirse Gabh\u00e1n \u00d3 Dubhthaigh}}; 21 October 1882 \u2013 10 June 1951) was an Irish politician, barrister and judge who served as President of the [[High Court (Ireland)|High Court]] from 1946 to 1951, a Judge of the [[High Court (Ireland)|High Court]] from 1936 to 1951 and [[Minister for Foreign Affairs and Trade|Minister for Foreign Affairs]] from January 1922 to July 1922. He served as a [[Teachta D\u00e1la]]\n(TD) for the [[Dublin County (D\u00e1il constituency)|Dublin County]] constituency from 1921 to 1923. He served as a [[Member of Parliament]] (MP) for the [[South County Dublin (UK Parliament constituency)|South County Dublin]] constituency from 1918 to 1921.<ref name=oireachtas_db>{{cite web|url=https://www.oireachtas.ie/en/members/member/George-Gavan-Duffy.D.1919-01-21/|title=George Gavan Duffy|work=Oireachtas Members Database|access-date=12 February 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Family==\n{{unreferenced section|date=March 2016}}\nGeorge Gavan Duffy was born at Rose Cottage, [[Rock Ferry]], [[Cheshire]], England, in 1882, the son of [[Charles Gavan Duffy|Sir Charles Gavan Duffy]] and his third wife, Louise (n\u00e9e Hall). His half-brother [[Frank Gavan Duffy|Sir Frank Gavan Duffy]] (1852\u20131936) was the fourth Chief Justice of the [[High Court of Australia]], sitting on the bench of the High Court from 1913-35.\n\nHis sister [[Louise Gavan Duffy]] came to Ireland in 1907, he taught in [[Patrick Pearse]]'s St Ita's school for girls ''Scoil \u00cdde'', was, with [[Mary Colum]] first Secretary of ''Cumann na mBan'', was out in the [[Easter Rising]] of 1916, in the GPO and Jacob's garrisons. She founded and ran ''Scoil Bhr\u00edde'', a bilingual school in [[Dublin]], which is still in operation. Louise came originally to Dublin, as her mother died in 1889.  George was raised by three half-sisters travelling from [[Austria]] and [[Germany]], at Guilloy, [[Nice]], [[France]]. He spoke fluent Italian and French received education from ''Petit Seminaire''. From there he was sent to [[Stonyhurst College]].\n\nHe qualified with a solicitor's firm in London in 1907. He married Margaret Sullivan, on 13 December 1908. They had two children, a son (Colum) and a daughter (M\u00e1ire). Colum Duffy was a legal scholar and law librarian at the [[Law Society of Ireland]].{{citation needed|date=March 2016}}\n\n==Early career==\nGavan Duffy qualified as a solicitor and practised in London. He defended [[Roger Casement|Sir Roger Casement]] at his trial for [[high treason]] after the Easter Rising. Although the case was unsuccessful and Casement executed, the trial had an enormous effect on Gavan Duffy and in 1917, when he was called to the [[Irish Bar]], he came to live in [[King's Inns]], Dublin, where he became immersed in Irish political life.\n\n==Political life==\n\n===Recognition efforts===\n{{more citations needed section|date=March 2016}}\nDuring the [[1918 Irish general election|1918 Westminster election]], he was elected as a [[Sinn F\u00e9in]] [[Member of Parliament|MP]] for [[South Dublin (UK Parliament constituency)|South County Dublin]].<ref name=elecs_irl>{{cite web|url=http://electionsireland.org/candidate.cfm?ID=1000|title=George Gavan Duffy|work=ElectionsIreland.org|accessdate=12 February 2012}}</ref>\n\nHe was sent to Paris to join [[Se\u00e1n T. O'Kelly]], as an envoy of the newly declared [[Irish Republic]]. Gavan Duffy published articles and pamphlets urging recognition of Ireland as a sovereign nation at the [[Paris Peace Conference, 1919|Paris Peace Conference]], which caused increasing embarrassment to the French establishment, who believed his publications were damaging Anglo-French relations.\n\nGavan Duffy and O'Kelly sought France's help against Britain when the treaties ending the [[First World War]] had not yet been signed; Britain had been France's main ally for most of the war, in which France had suffered enormous losses. In January 1919, the Sinn F\u00e9in-affiliated [[Irish Republican Army]] had also started the [[Anglo-Irish War|Irish War of Independence]] against Britain, and the new [[D\u00e1il]] had [[Irish Declaration of Independence|declared independence]] from the United Kingdom.\n\nFurther, the British position was that it was preparing a revised system of Irish Home Rule which would be effected after the Peace Conference, and that it had tried to solve the Irish Question at the [[Irish Convention]] in 1917, which Sinn F\u00e9in had boycotted. Sinn F\u00e9in had joined in the [[Conscription Crisis of 1918|campaign against conscription]] in 1918.\n\nIn consequence all the [[Allies of World War I]] saw the Sinn F\u00e9in movement as more or less hostile. A final letter of June 1919 demanding recognition and addressed to the French Prime Minister [[Georges Clemenceau]], the chairman of the Peace Conference, was not replied to.<ref>See [[National Archives of Ireland|NAI]] file DFA ES Paris 1919; Official Memorandum in support of Ireland's demand for recognition as a sovereign independent state. Presented to Georges Clemenceau and the members of the Paris Peace Conference by Sean T. O'Ceallaigh and George Gavan Duffy.</ref>\n\nFinally, after publishing a letter he had sent to Clemenceau in protest against the former mistreatment of [[Terence MacSwiney]] in prison in 1917, Gavan Duffy was banished from Paris. He was declared ''persona non grata'' in December 1920. He then went to Rome and from there travelled through Europe on behalf of the Ministry of the Irish Republic, without securing its recognition.\n\n===Anglo-Irish Treaty===\n[[File:The peacemakers- George Gavan Duffy, Erskine Childers, Robert Barton and Arthur Griffith in a group (28455606301).jpg|thumb|Duffy together with other members of the negotiation team (including Childers, Griffith, and Barton) in December 1921]]\nWhen [[\u00c9amon de Valera]] chose his plenipotentiaries to negotiate the [[Anglo-Irish Treaty]] in 1921; Gavan Duffy was chosen due mainly to his legal expertise. He protested against signing the Treaty but did so reluctantly, becoming the last person to sign. During the debates which followed in [[D\u00e1il \u00c9ireann]], Gavan Duffy stated that he would recommend the Treaty reluctantly but sincerely as he saw no alternative for the desired aim of independence.\n\n<blockquote>I do not love this treaty now any more than I loved it when I signed it, that I do not think that...is an adequate motive for rejection to point out that some of us signed the Treaty under duress, not to say that this treaty will not lead to permanent peace.  It is necessary before you reject the Treaty to go further than that and to produce to the people of Ireland a rational alternative.  My heart is with those who are against the Treaty, but my reason is against them, because I can see no rational alternative.<ref>D\u00e1il Debates, 21 December 1921</ref></blockquote>\n\nGavan Duffy placed the onus on the people who were responsible for drafting the Constitution of the Irish Free State to frame it in accordance with the terms of the Treaty. He disagreed, however, with Griffith's decision to show the draft constitution to [[British Prime Minister]] [[David Lloyd George|Lloyd George]] who immediately ordered that references to the [[King of the United Kingdom|King]] had to be inserted as well as an Oath of Allegiance. Lloyd George threatened to start a war if the Irish refused to sign; but Gavan Duffy did not believe it.\n\nOn 21 December 1921, he gave his main reason for supporting the treaty in the Dail, the impact of a potentially renewed war on the people, concluding:\n<blockquote>You may gamble on the prospects of a renewal of that horrible war, which I for one have only seen from afar, but which I know those who have so nobly withstood do not wish to see begun again without a clear prospect of getting further than they are to-day. We are told that this is a surrender of principle. If that be so, we must be asked to believe that every one of those who have gone before us in previous fights, and who in the end have had to lay down their arms or surrender to avert a greater evil to the people, have likewise been guilty of a breach of principle. I do not think an argument of that kind will get you much further. No! The solid principle, the solid basis upon which every honest man ought to make up his mind on this issue, may be summed up in the principle that we all claimed when it was first enunciated by the President, the principle of government by the [[consent of the governed]]. I say that no serious person here, whatever his feelings, knowing as he must what the people of this country think of the matter, will be doing his duty if, under these circumstances, he refuses to ratify the Treaty. Ratify it with the most dignified protest you can, ratify because you cannot do otherwise, but ratify it in the interests of the people you must.</blockquote>\n\n===Resignations===\nThis prompted him to resign but he was compelled to remain in office, serving as [[Minister for Foreign Affairs and Trade|Minister for Foreign Affairs]] from January 1922 to July 1922. On the outbreak of the [[Irish Civil War]] he resigned when the Provisional Government refused to effect a court order for [[habeas corpus]] in favour of [[George Plunkett (Irish Republican)|George Plunkett]] (a son of [[George Noble Plunkett|Count Plunkett]]), who was detained without charge with other republicans.\n\nHis tenure in office was cut short by his decision to resign again when the [[Executive Council of the Irish Free State]] abolished the Republican Courts and executed his good friend [[Erskine Childers (author)|Erskine Childers]].\n\nHe stood in the [[1923 Irish general election|1923 general election]] as an independent candidate but failed to be re-elected.\n\n==Barrister and judge==\n{{more citations needed|section|date=December 2017}}\nGavan Duffy returned to the [[Irish Bar]] and built up a large practice and was engaged in some notable constitutional cases such as the Land Annuities controversy in which he claimed that the [[Irish Free State]] could not be bound either in honour or in law to hand over annuities to Britain. He was appointed [[Senior Counsel]] in 1930 and Judge of the [[High Court (Ireland)|High Court]] in 1936. He acted as an unofficial legal advisor to [[\u00c9amon de Valera]] during the drafting of the 1937 [[Constitution of Ireland]] and was consulted on many issues pertaining to it. He was also a member of the commission to set up the second house of the [[Oireachtas]], [[Seanad \u00c9ireann]], in 1937. As president of the High Court he issues the ruling in [[State (Burke) v. Lennon]] that was upheld by the Supreme Court of Ireland.\n\nIn 1946, at the height of his legal career, he was appointed President of the [[High Court (Ireland)|High Court]], a position he held for the rest of his life. His most controversial judgement was in the ''Tilson Case'' heard in 1950, one year before his death, in which he applied the ''[[ne temere]]'' decree to the letter as de Valera's 1937 Irish Constitution gave the [[Roman Catholic Church in Ireland]] a \"special position\".<ref>[[Irish Law Times]] Report vol.86 (1952) pp. 49\u201373</ref> The [[Supreme Court of Ireland]] concurred but Gavan Duffy was criticised in some quarters for  his ruling.<ref>Finola Kennedy, ''Family, economy and government in Ireland''; ESRI, Dublin (1989) pp. 70\u201371.</ref><ref>Donal Barrington, ''The family and education''; The Irish Monthly, Irish Jesuit Province, 1953.</ref> He was a longstanding member of the Catholic organisation [[An R\u00edoghacht]].<ref>Maurice Curtis, ''A Challenge to Democracy: Militant Catholicism in Modern Ireland'', The History Press Ireland, 2010, p. 55<!-- ISSN/ISBN needed --></ref>\n\nIn 1945, Gavan Duffy had extended the [[Benefit of clergy|privilege of clergy]] to evidence heard by Catholic priests hearing [[Sacrament of Penance (Catholic Church)|confessions]].<!-- to the effect that a priest was not obliged to repeat the evidence to any other party, including a court of law. NOTE: Hasn't this always been the law of the confessional?? --> Proposals to reverse the privilege were published in 2012.<!-- What came of them?? --><ref>''Irish Daily Mail'', 21 May 2012, pp 1, 8. The case was ''Cook v. Carroll'' (1945) Irish Reports 165; a pregnant girl and her boyfriend had both confessed their affair to a priest, and the girl's family wanted the father's admission of paternity to the priest to be repeated in a court case for [[child support]]. The man denied paternity and Gavan Duffy ruled that the priest was not obliged to repeat what he had heard in the man's confession.</ref>\n\n==Death==\nGeorge Gavan Duffy died at his home in Bushy Park Road, [[Terenure]], Dublin, on 10 June 1951.{{citation needed|date=December 2017}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*Golding, G.M. ''George Gavan Duffy 1882\u20131951: a legal biography'' (Dublin, 1982)\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110607092009/http://historical-debates.oireachtas.ie/D/DT/D.T.192112210002.html Gavan-Duffy's speech on 21 Dec 1921, pp.86\u201389]\n*[http://difp.ie/viewdoc.asp?DocID=13 Letter to Clemenceau demanding recognition,  June 1919]\n* {{cite TIWW |article=Duffy, George Gavan |page=70 }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before = [[Arthur Griffith]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title  = {{nowrap|[[Minister for Foreign Affairs and Trade|Minister for Foreign Affairs]]}}\n       |years  = Jan 1922 \u2013 Jul 1922}}\n{{s-aft|after  = [[Arthur Griffith]]}}\n{{end}}\n{{4th Ministry of D\u00e1il \u00c9ireann}}\n{{Ministers for Foreign Affairs of Ireland}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gavan Duffy, George}}\n[[Category:1882 births]]\n[[Category:1951 deaths]]\n[[Category:Early Sinn F\u00e9in TDs]]\n[[Category:Ministers for Foreign Affairs (Ireland)]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for County Dublin constituencies (1801\u20131922)]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1918\u20131922]]\n[[Category:Members of the 1st D\u00e1il]]\n[[Category:Members of the 2nd D\u00e1il]]\n[[Category:Members of the 3rd D\u00e1il]]\n[[Category:Irish lawyers]]\n[[Category:Irish barristers]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the High Court (Ireland)]]\n[[Category:Alumni of King's Inns]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFamily:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 1913-35 \u2192 1913\u201335", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/George_Gavan_Duffy"}
