{"title_page": "Stanley Gange", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2016}}\n'''Edwin Stanley Gange''' (1871 \u2013 29 February 1944) was an English [[merchant]] and [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal]] politician.\n\n==Personal life and career==\nGange was born in [[Bristol]], the son of the Reverend Edwin Gorsuch Gange, a nationally known [[Baptist]] [[Minister (Christianity)|minister]] who was for nearly 25 years the [[pastor]] of the [[Broadmead Baptist Church|Broadmead Chapel]].   In 1895, at Bristol, he married Alice Maud Denning and they had two sons, William (b. 1896) and Gerald (b. 1900)<ref>[http://freepages.genealogy.rootsweb.ancestry.com/~publicbenefit/biogeh.html ''The Public Benefit Boot Company'']</ref> Gange went into trade and is usually described as a merchant.<ref>''Who was Who'', OUP, 2007</ref> He also had interests in property and was Director of Lennards, a Bristol property company.<ref>The Times, 1 November 1920 p19</ref>\n\n==Political and public life==\nGange was drawn into politics, his [[Nonconformist (Protestantism)|nonconformist]] religion and his commercial interests attracting him to the Liberal Party. He was a co-opted member of Bristol Town Council and was he Chairman of Bristol North Liberal Association during the time [[Augustine Birrell]] (also a Baptist) was [[Member of Parliament (UK)|MP]] for the constituency.<ref>''The Times House of Commons 1919''; Politico\u2019s Publishing, 2004 p27</ref> He involved himself in the public life of Bristol, serving as a [[Justice of the Peace]] and in 1931\u201332, he was [[High Sheriff of Bristol|Sheriff of Bristol]].<ref>''Who was Who'', OUP, 2007</ref>\n\nAfter a long Parliamentary and ministerial career, but one which ended in comparative failure with his resignation as [[Chief Secretary for Ireland]] in the aftermath of the [[Easter Rising]], Augustine Birrell decided not to contest the [[1918 United Kingdom general election|1918 general election]]. Bristol Liberals selected Gange as his successor and he fought [[Bristol North (UK Parliament constituency)|Bristol North]] as a [[Coalition government 1916-1922|Coalition Liberal]]. He was not opposed by the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Unionists]] and he was presumably awarded the [[Coalition coupon]]. In a three cornered fight with [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] and [[National Party (UK, 1917)|National Party]] candidates he won over 60% of the vote, with a majority of 6,393 over Labour. However he did not stand for re-election in 1922 and did not contest any further Parliamentary elections.<ref>F W S Craig, ''British Parliamentary Election Results 1918-1949''; Political Reference Publications, Glasgow, 1949 pp107 and 692</ref>\n\nGange retained his association with the Liberals after 1922, serving as the President of the Bristol Liberal Club after leaving [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|Parliament]].<ref>'' Southern History: The Journal of the Southern History Society '', Volumes 16-17; 1994 p146</ref>  After the political crisis which led to the formation of the [[National Government (United Kingdom)|National Government]] in 1931, he supported the [[National Liberal Party (UK, 1931)|Liberal Nationals]], lending his weight to campaigns supporting Robert Bernays, the National candidate in Bristol North.<ref>'' Southern History: The Journal of the Southern History Society '', Volumes 16-17; 1994 p134</ref>\n\n==Papers==\nThere are some papers relating to Gange deposited in the [[Bristol Archives]]. These are biographical notes, giving family and business details as well covering his political career. There news cuttings and a visitors\u2019 book relating to his time as Sheriff in 1931\u201332.<ref>http://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/a2a/records.aspx?cat=002-40872&cid=2&kw=#2)</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{succession box\n | title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Bristol North (UK Parliament constituency)|Bristol North]]\n | years  = [[1918 United Kingdom general election|1918]] \u2013 [[1922 United Kingdom general election|1922]]\n | before = [[Augustine Birrell]]\n | after  = [[Henry Guest]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gange, Stanley}}\n[[Category:1871 births]]\n[[Category:1944 deaths]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1918\u20131922]]\n[[Category:Liberal Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Councillors in Bristol]]\n[[Category:High Sheriffs of Bristol]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2016}}\n'''Edwin Stanley Gange''' (1871 \u2013 29 February 1944) was an English [[merchant]] and [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal]] politician.\n\n==Personal life and career==\nGange was born in [[Bristol]], the son of the Reverend Edwin Gorsuch Gange, a nationally known [[Baptist]] [[Minister (Christianity)|minister]] who was for nearly 25 years the [[pastor]] of the [[Broadmead Baptist Church|Broadmead Chapel]].   In 1895, at Bristol, he married Alice Maud Denning and they had two sons, William (b. 1896) and Gerald (b. 1900)<ref>[http://freepages.genealogy.rootsweb.ancestry.com/~publicbenefit/biogeh.html ''The Public Benefit Boot Company'']</ref> Gange went into trade and is usually described as a merchant.<ref>''Who was Who'', OUP, 2007</ref> He also had interests in property and was Director of Lennards, a Bristol property company.<ref>The Times, 1 November 1920 p19</ref>\n\n==Political and public life==\nGange was drawn into politics, his [[Nonconformist (Protestantism)|nonconformist]] religion and his commercial interests attracting him to the Liberal Party. He was a co-opted member of Bristol Town Council and was he Chairman of Bristol North Liberal Association during the time [[Augustine Birrell]] (also a Baptist) was [[Member of Parliament (UK)|MP]] for the constituency.<ref>''The Times House of Commons 1919''; Politico\u2019s Publishing, 2004 p27</ref> He involved himself in the public life of Bristol, serving as a [[Justice of the Peace]] and in 1931-32, he was [[High Sheriff of Bristol|Sheriff of Bristol]].<ref>''Who was Who'', OUP, 2007</ref>\n\nAfter a long Parliamentary and ministerial career, but one which ended in comparative failure with his resignation as [[Chief Secretary for Ireland]] in the aftermath of the [[Easter Rising]], Augustine Birrell decided not to contest the [[1918 United Kingdom general election|1918 general election]]. Bristol Liberals selected Gange as his successor and he fought [[Bristol North (UK Parliament constituency)|Bristol North]] as a [[Coalition government 1916-1922|Coalition Liberal]]. He was not opposed by the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Unionists]] and he was presumably awarded the [[Coalition coupon]]. In a three cornered fight with [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] and [[National Party (UK, 1917)|National Party]] candidates he won over 60% of the vote, with a majority of 6,393 over Labour. However he did not stand for re-election in 1922 and did not contest any further Parliamentary elections.<ref>F W S Craig, ''British Parliamentary Election Results 1918-1949''; Political Reference Publications, Glasgow, 1949 pp107 and 692</ref>\n\nGange retained his association with the Liberals after 1922, serving as the President of the Bristol Liberal Club after leaving [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|Parliament]].<ref>'' Southern History: The Journal of the Southern History Society '', Volumes 16-17; 1994 p146</ref>  After the political crisis which led to the formation of the [[National Government (United Kingdom)|National Government]] in 1931, he supported the [[National Liberal Party (UK, 1931)|Liberal Nationals]], lending his weight to campaigns supporting Robert Bernays, the National candidate in Bristol North.<ref>'' Southern History: The Journal of the Southern History Society '', Volumes 16-17; 1994 p134</ref>\n\n==Papers==\nThere are some papers relating to Gange deposited in the [[Bristol Archives]]. These are biographical notes, giving family and business details as well covering his political career. There news cuttings and a visitors\u2019 book relating to his time as Sheriff in 1931-32.<ref>http://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/a2a/records.aspx?cat=002-40872&cid=2&kw=#2)</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{succession box\n | title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Bristol North (UK Parliament constituency)|Bristol North]]\n | years  = [[1918 United Kingdom general election|1918]] \u2013 [[1922 United Kingdom general election|1922]]\n | before = [[Augustine Birrell]]\n | after  = [[Henry Guest]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gange, Stanley}}\n[[Category:1871 births]]\n[[Category:1944 deaths]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1918\u20131922]]\n[[Category:Liberal Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Councillors in Bristol]]\n[[Category:High Sheriffs of Bristol]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 1931-32 \u2192 1931\u201332 (2)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stanley_Gange"}
